<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">26789095</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2016</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>13</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>27</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1715-5320</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>41</Volume><Issue>2</Issue><PubDate><Year>2016</Year><Month>Feb</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Applied physiology, nutrition, and metabolism = Physiologie appliquee, nutrition et metabolisme</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Appl Physiol Nutr Metab</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effect of a high and low dose of caffeine on human lymphocyte activation in response to antigen stimulation.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>224</StartPage><EndPage>227</EndPage><MedlinePgn>224-7</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1139/apnm-2015-0456</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>This study investigated the effect of caffeine on antigen-stimulated lymphocyte activation. Six males rested for 3.5 h after ingesting 0 (PLA), 2, or 6 (6CAF) mg&#xb7;kg(-1) body mass of caffeine. The number of antigen-stimulated NK CD69(+) cells increased in 6CAF at 1 h compared with PLA (P = 0.021). Caffeine did not influence the number of antigen-stimulated CD69(+) T cells or the geometric mean fluorescence intensity expression of CD69 on antigen-stimulated lymphocytes, suggesting caffeine has little effect on antigen-stimulated lymphocyte activation.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Dulson</LastName><ForeName>Deborah K</ForeName><Initials>DK</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a AUT University, Sports Performance Research Institute New Zealand, Private Bag 92006, Auckland 1020, New Zealand.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bishop</LastName><ForeName>Nicolette C</ForeName><Ini